      <hedline>
        <hl1>When Alzheimer's Strikes Home</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Clifford Meirowitz letter on Jonathan Kozol's Aug 22 Op-Ed article on his father's deterioration from Alzheimer's disease; says it is not necessarily true that a family must first exhaust its savings before Medicaid will cover cost of chronic care</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Losing My Father, One Day at a Time,'' by Jonathan Kozol (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
        <p>I also support financing for research programs to advance early diagnosis and prevention of Alzheimer's disease. The rules that govern Medicare and Medicaid are complex and do require revision.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Losing My Father, One Day at a Time,'' by Jonathan Kozol (Op-Ed, Aug. 22):</p>
        <p>I also support financing for research programs to advance early diagnosis and prevention of Alzheimer's disease. The rules that govern Medicare and Medicaid are complex and do require revision.</p>
        <p>But it is not necessarily true that a family must first exhaust its savings before Medicaid will cover the cost of chronic care.</p>
        <p>There are transfer-of-asset rules that permit people to preserve assets legally and obtain the care they need. There are laws intended to prevent spousal impoverishment in the event of a long-term illness like Alzheimer's disease.</p>
        <p>With proper planning, families can preserve and protect their assets and still receive long-term care.</p>
        <p>CLIFFORD MEIROWITZ  New York, Aug. 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
